snippet.textDisplay:
There is another way to draw like a printer, make drawing quite easy, proove it with cameras and still cheat.

Setup of this cheat would be on the other hand quite scientific and challenging.

It all comes down to physics and carefull setup of flickering.
If your camera records at a fixed fps rate X and you are able to project an image from a projector straight on to the paper with another fixed refresh rate Y, syncing both devices (adjusting Y and X) can give an effect that a human eye would see an image on the paper, but cameras would only capture the 'bits of time' when the projector/screen is dark.

That way you could draw line by line seeing the picture overlay straight on the paper, but on the camera it would look like you had no help at all.

Come to think of it, this would make a very interesting video to shoot :)

EDIT: another method, easier to do and explain would be to use polarized light. It would be possible to emit polarized light onto the paper, block it from the camera (or cameras) but allow the human eye to see it. :3
snippet.textOriginal:
There is another way to draw like a printer, make drawing quite easy, proove it with cameras and still cheat.

Setup of this cheat would be on the other hand quite scientific and challenging.

It all comes down to physics and carefull setup of flickering.
If your camera records at a fixed fps rate X and you are able to project an image from a projector straight on to the paper with another fixed refresh rate Y, syncing both devices (adjusting Y  and X) can give an effect that a human eye would see an image on the paper, but cameras would only capture the 'bits of time' when the projector/screen is dark.

That way you could draw line by line seeing the picture overlay straight on the paper, but on the camera it would look like you had no help at all. 

Come to think of it, this would make a very interesting video to shoot :)

EDIT: another method, easier to do and explain would be to use polarized light. It would be possible to emit polarized light onto the paper, block it from the camera (or cameras) but allow the human eye to see it. :3

snippet.textDisplay: An image is projected onto the paper  with a light spectrum that the human eye + glasses can see but the overseeing camera cannot. The “artist” covers the projected color image he sees with a pencil that makes the seen light disappear, leaving only the penciled image. There is another method where the image is switched off “strobed” when the camera take a snapshot so fast the “artist” hardly notices. But some people may actually be that good that they need not cheat.

snippet.textDisplay: Yeah, but why would that be a big deal or be unusual? Tracing is common among artists, especially for anyone who illustrates. I can't have pencil lines in my comic book, but I'm also not going to risk my ink lines going out of bounds. So I'm going to trace my sketches to have a final inked version. This isn't a shocking revelation. That's like saying you suspect an actor wears makeup while performing on stage.

snippet.textDisplay:
This is awesome😳✨👏 🙌
Btw when I took sculpting and we had to sculpt our own bust 😳 our professor told us that whatever insecurities we have, we tend to unconsciously exaggerate those parts in our drawing or in my case, sculpture. Like if someone think they have small eyes they unconsciously make their eyes smaller, those conscious with their ears sculpt their ears that makes it more prominent and with the nose well…😅 bigger. Same with me, Im insecure with my nose and i had to scrap & slash my nose off my clay bust so many times 😅… I think you got the shape of your nose almost perfect but the shading is probably what is putting you off… the shading made it seem like the center of your nose is a lil bit larger than you think, which imo is not (compared to mine 😭… #bignoseclub orz 😞)
